I utilized Claude Sonnet for the task of creating the Report frontend and adding the report route
to record.js on the backend. I also utilized Claude Sonnet for brainstorming ways in which I could
protect against SQL injection and add transactions to the application. To verify the Report 
frontend and backend, I made sure to test the application dozens of times and ensure that the 
report populates accurate information on the frontend, even when data is modified. I also verified 
that Claude’s suggestions to protect against injection and add transactions led to a working 
application by performing dozens of application walkthroughs, and did my own research using 
resources like MongoDB, GitHub, and Stack Overflow to ensure that the changes I implemented have
the expected behavior and exactly how they work. I even modified the mongoSanitize statement in 
server.js to make it work for my particular application by specifying the mongoSanitize statement to 
my request body. Before, Claude suggested using a generic app.use(mongoSanitize()), which I discovered 
was trying to overwrite my request query. Since req.query isn't modified by the user, I made the 
adjustment to req.body specifically.
